Bullet Data Preparation for LIME Diagnostics Paper

Katherine Goode

September 25, 2020

This document contains code for preparing the raw bullet data sets (training, testing, and example matching signatures) to be used the paper Visual Diagnostics of a Model Explainer Tools for the Assessment of LIME Explanations.

NOTE The code chunks where the prepared data versions are shared have eval = FALSE. These code chunks must be run manually. This is done to help avoid any accidental changes of the data.

Load R packages:

library(cowplot)

Clean CCFs with lands

Rename some of the variables to match the structure of bullet_train_raw, select only variables of interest, and convert LEA labels to factors (for plotting purposes):

ccfs_withlands_raw_expanded <- 
  ccfs_withlands_raw %>%
  rename("study1" = "study.x", "barrel1" = "barrel.x", "bullet1" = "bullet.x", "land1" = "land.x",
         "study2" = "study.y", "barrel2" = "barrel.y", "bullet2" = "bullet.y", "land2" = "land.y") %>%
  select(
    study1, barrel1, bullet1, land1, 
    study2, barrel2, bullet2, land2,
    all_of(rf_features), 
    match
  ) %>%
  mutate(across(c(study1, barrel1, bullet1, land1, study2, barrel2, bullet2, land2), factor))

Create a version of the bullet_train_raw data with the land IDs expanded to multiple columns for plotting:

bullet_train_raw_expanded <- 
  bullet_train_raw %>%
  separate(land_id1, c("study1", "barrel1", "bullet1", "land1")) %>%
  separate(land_id2, c("study2", "barrel2", "bullet2", "land2")) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), factor)) %>%
  mutate(barrel1 = fct_relevel(barrel1, paste0("Br", 1:10)),
         barrel2 = fct_relevel(barrel2, paste0("Br", 1:10)))

Clean ccfs_withlands so the labels match bullet_train_raw:

ccfs_withlands_clean_expanded <- ccfs_withlands_raw_expanded %>%
  mutate(
    study1 = fct_recode(study1, "Hamby173" = "Hamby44"),
    study2 = fct_recode(study2, "Hamby173" = "Hamby44"),
    bullet1 = ifelse(barrel1 %in% letters, as.character(barrel1), as.character(bullet1)),
    barrel1 = ifelse(barrel1 %in% letters, "Unk", barrel1),
    bullet2 = ifelse(barrel2 %in% letters, as.character(barrel2), as.character(bullet2)),
    barrel2 = ifelse(barrel2 %in% letters, "Unk", barrel2)
    ) %>%
  mutate(
    study1 = fct_relevel(study1, "Hamby173", "Hamby252"),
    study2 = fct_relevel(study2, "Hamby173", "Hamby252"),
    barrel1 = paste0("Br", barrel1),
    bullet1 = paste0("B", bullet1),
    land1 = paste0("L", land1),
    barrel2 = paste0("Br", barrel2),
    bullet2 = paste0("B", bullet2),
    land2 = paste0("L", land2)
  ) %>% 
  mutate(across(where(is.character), factor)) %>%
  mutate(barrel1 = fct_relevel(barrel1, paste0("Br", 1:10)),
         barrel2 = fct_relevel(barrel2, paste0("Br", 1:10)))

Compare Dimensions to rtrees

The dimensions of the raw data:

bullet_train_raw %>% dim()
## [1] 84666    17

The dimension of the data once the observations with tank rash (flag != FALSE) are removed:

bullet_train_raw %>% filter(flag == FALSE) %>% dim()
## [1] 84255    17

The number of observations in the random forest rtrees:

length(bulletxtrctr::rtrees$predicted)
## [1] 83028

The number of rows in the training data with the flagged observations excluded does not match the number of observations used to train rtrees. In the Hare, Hofmann, and Carriquiry (2017), they describe removing four land impressions that were flagged for quality assessment:

  • Barrel 6 Bullet 2-1
  • Barrel 9 Bullet 2-4
  • Unknown Bullet B-2
  • Unknown Bullet Q-4

It is unclear which study these lands correspond to. The code below removes all comparisons that include these barrel, bullet, and land combinations:

bullet_train_filtered <- 
  bullet_train_raw %>%
  mutate(bbl1 = str_remove(land_id1, pattern = "Hamby252-|Hamby173-"),
         bbl2 = str_remove(land_id2, pattern = "Hamby252-|Hamby173-")) %>%
  filter(!(bbl1 %in% c("Br6-B2-L1", "Br9-B2-L4", "BrUnk-BB-L2", "BrUnk-BQ-L4") | 
           bbl2 %in% c("Br6-B2-L1", "Br9-B2-L4", "BrUnk-BB-L2", "BrUnk-BQ-L4"))) %>%
  select(-bbl1, -bbl2)

The dimensions now agree with the number of observations in rtrees:

dim(bullet_train_filtered)
## [1] 83028    17
length(bulletxtrctr::rtrees$predicted) == dim(bullet_train_filtered)[1]
## [1] TRUE

The code below removes observations based on Eric Hares code (available here), which he thinks may be the code used to train rtrees:

bullet_train_eric_filter <- 
  bullet_train_raw %>%
  separate(col = "land_id1", into = c("study1", "barrel1", "bullet1", "land1")) %>%
  separate(col = "land_id2", into = c("study2", "barrel2", "bullet2", "land2")) %>%
  filter(study1 != "Hamby173" | bullet1 != "BE") %>%
  filter(study2 != "Hamby173" | bullet2 != "BE")

Extracting the predictions on the training data from rtrees and using rtrees to make predictions on the filtered data:

rtrees_pred = predict(bulletxtrctr::rtrees, type = "prob")[,2]

new_pred = predict(bulletxtrctr::rtrees, 
                   bullet_train_filtered %>% 
                     select(rownames(bulletxtrctr::rtrees$importance)), type = "prob")[,2]

new_pred_full = predict(bulletxtrctr::rtrees, 
                        bullet_train_raw %>%
                          select(rownames(bulletxtrctr::rtrees$importance)), type = "prob")[,2]

Plot comparing the two predictions (we discovered that the predict function from random forest returns different results when applied to only the model (out-of-bag predictions) and the training data (regular predictions), so this is not a good way to test for agreement between training data and models):

data.frame(rtrees_pred = sort(rtrees_pred), new_pred = sort(new_pred)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(rtrees_pred, new_pred)) + 
  geom_point()

Plot showing distributions of predictions from rtrees and new predictions made on full training data (same comment here as above about not being able to use this to determine if we have the correct training data for the model):

data.frame(data = c(rep("rtrees", length(rtrees_pred)), 
                    rep("new predictions on full data", length(new_pred_full))), pred = c(rtrees_pred, new_pred_full)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = pred, fill = data)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.75)

Preparing Data

Determine the number of total study-barrel-bullet-lands in the data:

length(unique(bullet_train_raw %>% pull(land_id1)))
## [1] 411

Determine the number of total study-barrel-bullet-lands in the data when observations with tank rash are excluded:

length(unique(bullet_train_raw %>% filter(flag == FALSE) %>% pull(land_id1)))
## [1] 410

There is only one less land id when the cases with tank rash are excluded. The code below shows that this case is Hamby252-Br9-B2-L4 since there are no rows in the filtered data without Hamby252-Br9-B2-L4 as one of the land ids:

length(unique(
  bullet_train_raw %>% filter(flag == TRUE) %>% filter(
    land_id1 != "Hamby252-Br9-B2-L4",
    land_id2 != "Hamby252-Br9-B2-L4"
  ) %>% pull(land_id1)
))
## [1] 0

Using the data with the flagged lands removed, select only variables of use for the paper, add a case variable, and rename same_source as samesource:

bullet_train <- 
  bullet_train_filtered %>%
  select(-lag, -abs_lag, -overlap, -signature_length, -flag) %>%
  mutate(case = factor(1:n())) %>%
  rename("samesource" = "same_source") %>%
  select(case, land_id1, land_id2, everything())

Add a variable to the training data with the random forest probability in support of a match using the random forest model rtrees from bulletxtrctr:

bullet_features <- rownames(bulletxtrctr::rtrees$importance)
bullet_train$rfscore <- 
  bulletxtrctr::rtrees %>%
  predict(bullet_train %>% select(all_of(bullet_features)), type = "prob") %>%
  data.frame() %>%
  pull(TRUE.)

Save the prepared data as a csv file:

write.csv(
  x = bullet_train, 
  file = "../data/bullet-train.csv", 
  row.names = FALSE
)

Also, save the original and prepared data as a zip files (for uploading to the GitHub repository):

zip(

Preparing the data from sets 1 and 11 for analysis:

hamby224_set1_cleaned <-
  hamby224_set1 %>%
  # Remove unneeded variables
  select(-bullet_score,-land1,-land2,-aligned,-striae,-features) %>%
  # Rename bullet and land variables
  rename(
    bullet1 = bulletA,
    bullet2 = bulletB,
    land1 = landA,
    land2 = landB
  ) %>%
  # Create study and set variables and change levels of bullet and land
  # variables to match those in the training data
  mutate(
    study = factor("Hamby224"),
    set = factor("Set1"),
    bullet1 = recode(factor(bullet1), "1" = "B1", "2" = "B2", "Q" = "BUnk"),
    bullet2 = recode(factor(bullet2), "1" = "B1", "2" = "B2", "Q" = "BUnk"),
    land1 = paste0("L", land1),
    land2 = paste0("L", land2)
  ) %>%
  # Order the variables as desired
  select(study, set, bullet1, land1, bullet2, land2, all_of(rf_features), samesource, rfscore)

hamby224_set11_cleaned <- 
  hamby224_set11 %>%
  # Remove unneeded variables
  select(-bullet_score,-land1,-land2,-aligned,-striae,-features) %>%
  # Rename bullet and land variables
  rename(
    bullet1 = bulletA,
    bullet2 = bulletB,
    land1 = landA,
    land2 = landB
  ) %>%
  # Create study and set variables and change levels of bullet and land
  # variables to match those in the training data
  mutate(
    study = factor("Hamby224"),
    set = factor("Set11"),
    bullet1 = recode(factor(bullet1), "Bullet 1" = "B1", "Bullet 2" = "B2", "Bullet I" = "BUnk"),
    bullet2 = recode(factor(bullet2), "Bullet 1" = "B1", "Bullet 2" = "B2", "Bullet I" = "BUnk"),
    land1 = str_remove(land1, "and "),
    land2 = str_remove(land2, "and ")
  ) %>%
  # Order the variables as desired
  select(study, set, bullet1, land1, bullet2, land2, all_of(rf_features), samesource, rfscore)

Join the two cleaned Hamby 224 sets into one testing set, remove duplicate comparisons, create a case variable, and create land ids based on the study, set, bullet, and land (remove those variables afterwards):

bullet_test_extra_vars <-
  # Join the two data sets
  bind_rows(hamby224_set1_cleaned, hamby224_set11_cleaned) %>%
  # Remove duplicate comparisons
  filter(!(bullet1 == "BUnk" & bullet2 == "B1"),
         !(bullet1 == "BUnk" & bullet2 == "B2"),
         !(bullet1 == "B2" & bullet2 == "B1")) %>%
  # Create a case and land_id variables
  mutate(
    case = factor(1:length(study)),
    land_id1 = paste(study, set, bullet1, land1, sep = "-"),
    land_id2 = paste(study, set, bullet2, land2, sep = "-")
  ) # Leave the extra variables for plotting

# Select and order variables to keep for analysis
bullet_test <- bullet_test_extra_vars %>%
  select(case, land_id1, land_id2, all_of(rf_features), samesource, rfscore)

Remaining comparisons included in the test data after the duplicate comparisons are removed:

plot_grid(
  bullet_test_extra_vars %>%
    filter(set == "Set1") %>%
    count(bullet1, land1, bullet2, land2) %>%
    ggplot(aes(
      x = land1, y = land2, fill = n
    )) +
    geom_tile() +
    facet_grid(bullet2 ~ bullet1) +
    scale_fill_distiller(palette = "GnBu", direction = 1) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(aspect.ratio = 1),
  bullet_test_extra_vars %>%
    filter(set == "Set11") %>%
    count(bullet1, land1, bullet2, land2) %>%
    ggplot(aes(
      x = land1, y = land2, fill = n
    )) +
    geom_tile() +
    facet_grid(bullet2 ~ bullet1) +
    scale_fill_distiller(palette = "GnBu", direction = 1) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(aspect.ratio = 1),
  align = "hv"
)

Example Matching Signatures

The following code trims the data provided by Heike of two matching bullet-land signatures.

Import the data (provided by Heike and CSAFE):

if (!file.exists("../data/raw/signatures.rds")) unzip("../data/raw/signatures.rds.zip")
signatures <- readRDS("../data/raw/signatures.rds")

Structure of the data:

Create a land variable based on the source variable, select only variables necessary for the manuscript, and rename sig as y:

signatures_trimmed <-
  signatures %>%
  mutate(land = c("Signature 1", "Signature 2")[as.factor(source)]) %>%
  select(land, x, sig) %>%
  rename(y = sig)

Export the trimmed data as a csv file:

write.csv(
  x = signatures_trimmed,
  file = "../data/example-signatures.csv",
  row.names = FALSE
)

Also, save the original and prepared data as a zip files (for uploading to the GitHub repository):

zip(
  zipfile = "../data/example-signatures.csv.zip", 
  files = "../data/example-signatures.csv"
)
